
Step 1: Install WSL
Open Command Prompt or PowerShell as Administrator:
wsl --install
Install Ubuntu:
wsl --install -d Ubuntu

Step 2: Install Java

sudo apt update
sudo apt install openjdk-8-jdk -y
java -version

Step 3: Set `JAVA_HOME`

Find the Java path:
readlink -f $(which java) | sed "s:bin/java::"

Open `.bashrc`:
nano ~/.bashrc

Add:

export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-8-openjdk-amd64
export PATH=$PATH:$JAVA_HOME/bin

Apply and verify:
source ~/.bashrc
echo $JAVA_HOME


Step 4: Download and Extract Hadoop
wget https://downloads.apache.org/hadoop/common/hadoop-3.3.6/hadoop-3.3.6.tar.gz
tar -xvzf hadoop-3.3.6.tar.gz
mv hadoop-3.3.6 hadoop

Step 5: Set Hadoop Environment Variables

nano ~/.bashrc
Add:
export HADOOP_HOME=~/hadoop
export PATH=$PATH:$HADOOP_HOME/bin:$HADOOP_HOME/sbin


Apply:
source ~/.bashrc


Step 6: Configure Hadoop
Go to the configuration directory:
cd ~/hadoop/etc/hadoop


6.1 Configure `core-site.xml`
nano core-site.xml
<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>fs.defaultFS</name>
        <value>hdfs://localhost:9000</value>
    </property>
</configuration>


6.2 Configure `hdfs-site.xml`

nano hdfs-site.xml
<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>dfs.replication</name>
        <value>1</value>
    </property>
</configuration>

6.3 Configure `mapred-site.xml`

nano mapred-site.xml
<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>mapreduce.framework.name</name>
        <value>yarn</value>
    </property>
</configuration>


6.4 Configure `yarn-site.xml`

nano yarn-site.xml
<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>yarn.nodemanager.aux-services</name>
        <value>mapreduce_shuffle</value>
    </property>
</configuration>


Step 7: Configure `hadoop-env.sh`
nano ~/hadoop/etc/hadoop/hadoop-env.sh


Set:
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-8-openjdk-amd64


Step 8: Configure SSH

Install SSH:
sudo apt install openssh-server -y


Generate an SSH key:
ssh-keygen -t rsa


Press Enter to accept the default settings and keep the password empty.
Authorize the key:
cat ~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys


Start SSH:
sudo service ssh start


Test:
ssh localhost
Type `yes` when prompted.

Step 9: Format the NameNode

hdfs namenode -format

Step 10: Start Hadoop Services

start-dfs.sh
start-yarn.sh


Step 11: Verify Running Services
jps
Expected processes include:

text
NameNode
DataNode
SecondaryNameNode
ResourceManager
NodeManager
Jps


Step 12: Access Hadoop Web Interfaces
HDFS NameNode: `http://localhost:9870`
YARN ResourceManager: `http://localhost:8088`

Step 13: Test HDFS Operations
Create a directory:
hdfs dfs -mkdir /test

Create a sample file:
echo "Hello Hadoop" > file.txt

Upload it to HDFS:
hdfs dfs -put file.txt /test

View the file:
hdfs dfs -cat /test/file.txt
